&lt;p>It’s generally accepted that the trial to understand the effects of weedkillers on plants isn’t conducted well.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>A bioassay reveals the effects for the plant to assimilate the nutrients.&lt;/p>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>A bioassay is a measurement of the concentration or potency of a substance by its effect on living cells or tissues.&lt;/p>
&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;p>This technique will tell you if the poison is present in the plant.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>In the image above, Charles thinks the concentration isn’t very high in his trial but it’s definitely present…&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="where-is-present">Where is present&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>Often, it’s present in horse manure, but also you can find it in cow manure or hay.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Even a 10-year-old manure will contain it.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="how-to-heal-the-contaminated-soil">How to heal the contaminated soil&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>You will need about 10 days of warm days and enough watering to break down the compounds in aminopyralid weedkiller.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>It’s the soil life that will break down the poisons.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
